\pard\plain \sa160\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs48\b1 Bargaining with God}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\i1 Genesis 18:16\endash 33; [19:1\endash 38]}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs32 Setting the Stage}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs22\b1 Theme.}{\f0\fs24  We\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve all probably questioned God at some point. When we witness human suffering, we may wonder why He allows such experiences to persist. When disasters inflict tragedy and destruction, we may question why He chooses not to intervene. We wonder what, if anything, devastating situations can teach us about God\u8217\'92s righteousness. We may even go so far as to question whether God is truly just.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 This is exactly what Abraham did in Gen 18. After hearing that God was planning to destroy Sodom and Gomorrah, he questioned God directly and tried to negotiate pardon for Sodom: Would God still destroy the city if He found 50 righteous people there? What about 45? Would He pardon it for as few as 10? Throughout his bargaining, Abraham wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t disrespectful. Rather, his questions showed his concern for upholding God\u8217\'92s reputation for righteousness and justice. In all his negotiating, Abraham\u8217\'92s chief concern was to know, \u8220\'93Will not the Judge of all the earth do right?\u8221\'94 (Gen 18:25 }{\f0\fs24\scaps niv}{\f0\fs24 ). And as a result of Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s actions, God showed him a little more of His character: He is indeed just and merciful, but maybe not in the ways we expect.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Grigoni, M. R., Custis, M., Mangum, D., & Whitehead, M. M. (2012). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/csabraham?ref=Bible.Ge18.16-33&off=10&ctx=CHAPTER+6%0a~Bargaining+with+God%0aGenesis+18"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Abraham: Following God\loch\af4\hich\af4\dbch\af4\uc1\u8217\'92s Promise\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Ge 18:16\endash 33). Bellingham, WA: Lexham Press.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs22\b1 Literary Context:}{\f0\fs24  Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s bargaining with God in Gen 18:16\endash 33 fits into the larger section of Gen 18\endash 19, which begins with three men visiting Abraham and ends with Lot narrowly escaping from the destruction of Sodom. In some ways, though, the story actually began earlier in Abraham\u8217\'92s life, when he and Lot separated (see Gen 13). Lot chose the fertile Jordan Valley, in which Sodom was located, and Abraham took Canaan (Gen 13:5\endash 12). Here, we find the first reference to the wickedness of Sodom (Gen 13:13).}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Later, Abraham came to Lot\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s defense after a group of Mesopotamian kings sacked Sodom and made off with spoils and captives, including Lot (Gen 14:11\endash 12). Abraham defeated the Mesopotamian kings, rescued his nephew, and restored Sodom\u8217\'92s possessions (Gen 14:13\endash 16). When the king of Sodom failed to show appreciation for Abraham\u8217\'92s intervention, Abraham disassociated himself from the ruler (Gen 14:21\endash 24; see Chapter 3). In establishing the wickedness of Sodom, the narrative sets the stage for its later destruction.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Grigoni, M. R., Custis, M., Mangum, D., & Whitehead, M. M. (2012). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/csabraham?ref=Bible.Ge18.16-33&off=1218&ctx=the+ways+we+expect.%0a~Literary+Context:+Ab"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Abraham: Following God\loch\af4\hich\af4\dbch\af4\uc1\u8217\'92s Promise\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Ge 18:16\endash 33). Bellingham, WA: Lexham Press.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f1\fs22\b1 Historical & Cultural Background:}{\f0\fs24  We don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t know the precise locations of Sodom and Gomorrah, though they were most likely situated somewhere around the Dead Sea (\u8220\'93the sea of the salt\u8221\'94; Gen 14:3). The traditional view is that Sodom and the related \u8220\'93cities of the Plain\u8221\'94 (Gen 13:12) were on the south end of the Dead Sea. Since Lot escaped to a city called Zoar (Gen 19:22), and there was a city at the southern point of the Dead Sea bearing that name, this location is possible. However, when Lot and Abraham first separated, the text says Lot chose \u8220\'93the plain of the Jordan\u8221\'94 (Gen 13:11), which typically refers to the lush Jordan Valley\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 an area northeast of the Dead Sea. The place name \u8220\'93the Plain\u8221\'94 is also used here in the destruction of Sodom episode (Gen 19:17, 25, 28\endash 29) and has been associated with Sodom since Gen 13:12.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Grigoni, M. R., Custis, M., Mangum, D., & Whitehead, M. M. (2012). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/csabraham?ref=Bible.Ge18.16-33&off=2246&ctx=+later+destruction.%0a~Historical+%26+Cultura"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Abraham: Following God\loch\af4\hich\af4\dbch\af4\uc1\u8217\'92s Promise\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Ge 18:16\endash 33). Bellingham, WA: Lexham Press.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f3\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Recent archaeological excavations also support the northern location. Within this \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Plain\u8221\'94 area, archaeologists have uncovered several small \u8220\'93tells\u8221\'94 or mounds containing the ruins of ancient cities. Nearby is a much larger tell thought to be the most prominent of all the cities of the Plain\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Sodom\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 now known as Tell el-Hammam.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 Archaeologists digging at Tell el-Hammam have uncovered a layer of ash nearly six-and-a-half feet deep in certain places. Within this ash layer, they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve found various artifacts believed to be from the time of Abraham. They\u8217\'92ve also found the remains of bodies and artifacts that have been smashed and burned, but not in a manner typical of warfare or earthquakes. Archaeologists describe \u8220\'93skeletons covered by architectural debris, limbs twisted out of normal positions, some thrown on their faces with hyperextended joints, and surrounded in the matrix by human bone scatter such as pieces of ribs, the ends of long bones, and skull fragments.\u8221\'94 The remains may tell the story of Gen 19\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a catastrophe Abraham was trying to prevent.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 Ultimately, Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s bargaining on behalf of Sodom was not enough to spare the city. God couldn\u8217\'92t find at least 10 righteous people (Gen 18:32), and He rained fire and brimstone on both Sodom and Gomorrah (Gen 19:24\endash 25). Yet Abraham\u8217\'92s intercession did result in Lot being spared. As Abraham looked down on the ashes of the cities, the story tells us that \u8220\'93God remembered Abraham\u8221\'94 and delivered Lot from the destruction (Gen 19:28\endash 29). For several generations, this layer of ash and its remains reminded people of God\u8217\'92s deliverance for the righteous and His wrath against the wicked.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Grigoni, M. R., Custis, M., Mangum, D., & Whitehead, M. M. (2012). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/csabraham?ref=Bible.Ge18.16-33&off=3076&ctx=+since+Gen+13:12.%0a+%0a~Recent+archaeologica"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Abraham: Following God\loch\af4\hich\af4\dbch\af4\uc1\u8217\'92s Promise\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Ge 18:16\endash 33). Bellingham, WA: Lexham Press.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs32 A Closer Look}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 This story begins with Abraham accompanying his three visitors as they depart (Gen 18:16). When they reached a place where they could look down on the city of Sodom, God deliberated\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 either to Himself or to the three visitors\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 about whether He should inform Abraham of His plans to destroy the city (Gen 18:17). As He was considering, God repeated to Himself the promise He made to Abraham (Gen 18:18\endash 19).}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 While previously God articulated the promise several times, this is the only time He voiced the promise without Abraham as His audience (see Gen 12:1\endash 3, 7; 13:14\endash 17; 15:1\endash 21; 17:1\endash 21). God began by reflecting on an aspect of the promise that had been present from the start: that Abraham would become a great and mighty nation that would bless all the nations of the earth (Gen 18:18; see 12:2\endash 3).}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 God then stated, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I have chosen [Abraham]\u8221\'94 (Gen 18:19). With this statement, the theme of divine election\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 implicit in the narrative thus far\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 becomes an explicit aspect of Abraham\u8217\'92s story and experience as well as that of God\u8217\'92s chosen people (see Deut 7:6\endash 8). God\u8217\'92s individual election of Abraham would eventually develop into God\u8217\'92s collective election of Israel. In both Abraham\u8217\'92s life and the life of the Israel, election entails blessing and protection for the chosen (Deut 4:39; Isa 65:9), as well as an expectation of obedience to the One who elects (Deut 4:40; 7:9\endash 11; Amos 3:2).}
