\pard\plain \intbl\itap1\sa160\qj{\f1\fs20\b1 Quick Bit}{\f0\fs22  The Hebrew word }{\f0\fs22\i1 tsedeq}{\f0\fs22  (often translated \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93righteousness\u8221\'94) is often used to refer to what is right or fair (see Lev 19:36). When translated as \u8220\'93justice,\u8221\'94 it carries a legal sense of innocence (see Deut 16:20). In his speeches, for example, Job claimed that his \u8220\'93vindication,\u8221\'94 or }{\f0\fs22\i1 tsedeq}{\f0\fs22 , was at stake (Job 6:29). Often, }{\f0\fs22\i1 tsedeq}{\f0\fs22  is used to refer to God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s \u8220\'93righteous\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93just\u8221\'94 judgments (Psa 9:7\endash 8; Jer 11:20). It appears with }{\f0\fs22\i1 mishpat}{\f0\fs22 , or \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93judgment,\u8221\'94 in many instances (Psa 33:5; Prov 1:3; Isa 56:1).}
