\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 God continued by discussing }{\f0\fs24\i1 why}{\f0\fs24  He chose Abraham. In His previous reiterations of the promise, He had revealed only the results of its fulfillment: that Abraham would have many descendants, become a great nation, and be a blessing. Here, He added a reason: God chose Abraham \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93to do righteousness and justice\u8221\'94 (Gen 18:19b). Abraham was to instruct his children and his entire household in God\u8217\'92s ways, in righteousness, and in justice. God was about to give Abraham an opportunity to debate these topics, as these very themes would drive Abraham in his intercession for Sodom.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 When God told Abraham that He was considering destroying Sodom and Gomorrah because of their sin, Abraham was troubled. He had risked his life to help these cities when he defeated the Mesopotamian kings in Gen 14 (see Chapter 3). Even so, Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s chief concern centered on God\u8217\'92s righteousness and justice.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s first question to God demonstrates his concern for justice: \u8220\'93Will you also sweep away the righteous with the wicked?\u8221\'94 (Gen 18:23). Abraham was distressed that in destroying Sodom, God might also destroy any righteous people living there. Such an act would violate God\u8217\'92s righteousness and justice since He would be destroying persons undeserving of such punishment.}
