\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Abraham used strong language to voice his disapproval, twice repeating, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Far be it from you \u8230\'85\u8221\'94 (Gen 18:25). This phrase is a strong way of expressing disapproval, equivalent to saying \u8220\'93certainly not.\u8221\'94 David later used this phrase to emphasize that he refused to harm Saul, God\u8217\'92s anointed one (1 Sam 26:11). Abraham\u8217\'92s use of the phrase expresses how unthinkable it seemed to him that God, the just Judge of the earth, would destroy the innocent along with the guilty. He began by asking God to spare the city if there were 50 righteous people in it (Gen 18:24).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 After God agreed to this request (Gen 18:26), Abraham started to bargain for lower numbers. He did so with respect and humility, recognizing his position before God (\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I am dust and ashes\u8221\'94; Gen 18:27) and being careful not to overstep his place (\u8220\'93Please, let not my Lord be angry\u8221\'94; Gen 18:30, 32). Each time he spoke, Abraham asked that God spare the city for the sake of fewer righteous people. With each lower number, Abraham demonstrated greater faith in God\u8217\'92s mercy as he asked God to spare an entire city of wicked people for the sake of only a few righteous.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 We don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t know why the negotiation ended at 10 righteous people (Gen 18:32). It is possible that the number 10 represented totality for the author of the story. Regardless of the reason, Abraham had made his point by the time the bargaining ended. He had appealed to God\u8217\'92s mercy, and God had agreed to spare the entire city for the sake of 10 righteous people.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 It is important to note that Abraham didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t try to convince God to change His plans. As one scholar says, \u8220\'93Abraham was not trying to talk God into doing something against his will, for he was convinced of the righteousness of God.\u8221\'94 God\u8217\'92s justice would prohibit Him from punishing the innocent, and His mercy would allow Him to save the wicked from punishment. Abraham, who was chosen \u8220\'93to do righteousness and justice\u8221\'94 and to instruct his descendants to do the same (Gen 18:19), showed a clear understanding of these facets of God\u8217\'92s character.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 Ultimately, Sodom lacked even 10 righteous people, and God destroyed both Sodom and Gomorrah by raining down fire and brimstone (Gen 19:24\endash 25). Even so, Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s intercession was not futile. God showed His mercy in a way that exceeded Abraham\u8217\'92s negotiation.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 After the cities\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92 destruction, Abraham returned to the place where he had negotiated with God and looked down on the ashes where the cities once stood. At this point, the narrative explains that when God destroyed the cities, He \u8220\'93remembered Abraham\u8221\'94 and delivered Lot (Gen 19:29). The term }{\f0\fs24\i1 zakhar}{\f0\fs24 , meaning \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93to remember,\u8221\'94 is often used in the context of God remembering and staying loyal to His covenant (Exod 2:24; Psa 105:8). Here, it speaks to the privileged position Abraham held (\u8220\'93I have chosen him\u8221\'94; Gen 18:19) and indicates that God demonstrated mercy in the midst of judgment.}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f5\fs24\i1 Study Questions}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\li360\fi-360\sa160\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 1.\tab God chose Abraham \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93to do righteousness and justice\u8221\'94 and to teach his descendants to keep the way of God. In what ways does your life reflect these aspects of God\u8217\'92s character? How can you better demonstrate God\u8217\'92s righteousness and justice to others?}
\par\pard\plain \li360\sa160\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \tx360\li360\fi-360\sa160\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 2.\tab Think of tragedies or injustices you have seen or experienced. Did they cause you to doubt the justice of God? Have you ever experienced a situation, like Abraham, where you questioned God? What have these experiences taught you about His nature?\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Grigoni, M. R., Custis, M., Mangum, D., & Whitehead, M. M. (2012). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/csabraham?ref=Bible.Ge18.16-33&off=10339"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Abraham: Following God\loch\af4\hich\af4\dbch\af4\uc1\u8217\'92s Promise\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Ge 18:16\endash 33). Bellingham, WA: Lexham Press.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs32 Application}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 We don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t often approach God the way Abraham did in Gen 18:16\endash 33. We tend to be leery of questioning or negotiating with Him. It seems disrespectful or even sacrilegious to question God or voice our discontent. However, the Bible contains many examples of people who did just that\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and they did so in a respectful manner.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Sometimes we try to bargain with God. We promise certain behaviors or actions if God will grant our requests. This type of bargaining shows a faulty understanding of what God desires. When Abraham negotiated with God, he did not do so based on what he could bring. He did not say, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93God, if you spare Sodom, I\u8217\'92ll offer extra sacrifices.\u8221\'94 Instead, Abraham negotiated based on God\u8217\'92s character, appealing to His justice and righteousness. In doing so, Abraham showed that he understood what is important to God.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 Other righteous people in the Bible also focused on God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s character when they approached God. When Moses asked God to refrain from punishing Israel for the golden calf incident, he appealed specifically to God\u8217\'92s reputation and His faithfulness, asking God how it would look to the Egyptians if He destroyed His own people (Exod 32:12). The psalmists wrestled with suffering and pain and presented their complaints to God, yet always with a focus on His character. Even Job\u8217\'92s complaints were based on a view of God\u8217\'92s attributes; Job could not reconcile his understanding of God\u8217\'92s righteousness with the severe suffering he was experiencing.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 In the Sermon on the Mount, Jesus encouraged His followers to approach God in prayer. God is not afraid of our questions; He wants to talk with us and hear our struggles. We can tell Him exactly what we are going through and trust that He understands our concerns and weaknesses. Yet Jesus also instructed His followers to put God first\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 to \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness\u8221\'94 (Matt 6:33 }{\f0\fs24\scaps esv}{\f0\fs24 ). God may not respond in the way we expect or want Him to, and we will not always understand how His mercy and grace is working to faithfully complete His work in our lives (1 Cor 13:12; Phil 1:6). However, we can be confident that the Judge of all the earth will do right.}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f5\fs24\i1 Study Questions}
